04434nam a22005055i 9780773569553DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735695537 a10.1515/97807735695532doi  a(DE-B1597)656852  a(OCoLC)76898610  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPT405bF237 2001eb 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a830.9/8/090481 aFachinger, Petra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRewriting Germany from the Margins :b“Other” German Literature of the 1980s and 1990s /cPetra Fachinger. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tWriting Back to Keller and Goethe: Franco Biondi and Akif Pirinçci -- t(Post)colonial Picaresque: Kerstin Jentzsch and Thomas Brussig -- tRe-Placing Language: The Poetry of Zehra Çirak and José F.A. Oliver -- tRewriting Home: The Border Writing of Barbara Honigmann and Renan Demirkan -- tRewriting Autobiography: Lea Fleischmann and Richard Chaim Schneider -- tRewriting Turkey: Barbara Frischmuth and Hanne Mede-Flock -- tWriting Back to Liberal Discourse: Feridun Zaimoglu’s Grotesque Realism -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe "margins" in Petra Fachinger's work are occupied largely by second-generation migrant writers from Spain, Italy, and Turkey, German Jewish writers of diverse ethnic origins, and writers born in the GDR. She demonstrates that during the 1980s and 1990s writers from various cultural backgrounds engaged in oppositional discourse to construct their own version of Germany and write back to the German canon. While most studies of texts by minority writers in Germany favour content over form, Fachinger focuses on identifying counter-discursive strategies, and applies postcolonial theory concerned with textual resistance to the German situation. In doing so, this study effectively relates marginal writing in Germany to similar forms of writing in other national and cultural contexts. The oppositional impulse, whether manifested in counter-canonical discourse, postcolonial picaresque, hybridity, rewriting of genre, or grotesque realism, is prompted by the exclusionary politics of the dominant culture. The discursive strategies used by the authors discussed to rewrite Germany expose the assumptions that underlie German public discourse and destabilize notions of Germanness, Jewishness, and Turkishness. Fachinger's reading of texts by marginal writers in Germany, all of whom endeavour to resist marginalization while simultaneously experiencing or even celebrating the margin as a site of empowerment, was motivated by the absence of comparative studies of such writing. Rewriting Germany from the Margins demonstrates the necessity and usefulness of comparative approaches to minority discourses across national and cultural borders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356955340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773569553423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773569553/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles